    summary: `Edi Rama is now the longest-serving prime minister in Albanian history, and after winning a fourth consecutive term in May 2025 with over 52% of the vote and 83 out of 140 parliamentary seats, he's showing no signs of slowing down. The Socialist Party (PS) didn't just win—they increased their majority, defying predictions that corruption scandals (the Tirana mayor arrested, the Kukës mayor detained, the infamous incinerator affair, the 5D scandal) would finally sink them. Rama's pitch was simple: EU membership by 2030. It's an audacious promise—Albania has been a candidate since 2014, formally started accession talks in 2022, and is nowhere near meeting the rule of law benchmarks Brussels demands. But in a country where average wages hover around €600 per month, where youth unemployment is 24%, and where tens of thousands emigrate annually, the EU dream is the only game in town. His main challenger was Sali Berisha, the 80-year-old former president and prime minister who's awaiting trial on corruption charges and whom the U.S. State Department has labeled "significantly corrupt" and banned from entry. The opposition Democratic Party (PD) is in disarray—Berisha's legal troubles, internal feuds, and the party's inability to articulate a vision beyond "Rama is corrupt" left them with just 36 seats. OSCE observers said the elections were "competitive and well-run" but lacked a "level playing field," citing the PS's widespread misuse of public resources and institutional power. In November 2025, Rama is consolidating his fourth term, but the real question is whether he can deliver on EU membership or whether Albania is stuck in permanent limbo.

Albania's political system is a parliamentary democracy, but in practice, it functions as a dominant-party system under Rama's PS. The president, Bajram Begaj (elected in 2022), is largely ceremonial—real power rests with the prime minister. Rama, a former mayor of Tirana and contemporary artist, has led the PS since 2005 and the government since 2013. His political brand mixes technocratic competence (he's pushed through judicial reforms, fought organized crime, digitized government services) with populist theatrics (he live-streams cabinet meetings, trolls opponents on social media, gives speeches in multiple languages). He's cultivated a strongman image—charismatic, unflappable, dismissive of critics. The PS controls the parliament, the judiciary (through judicial appointments), and most municipalities. The opposition is fragmented: the PD, led by Berisha despite his legal troubles, lacks credibility and organizational capacity. Smaller parties (the Socialist Movement for Integration, the Freedom Party) have minimal influence. Albania's EU accession process is the defining political narrative. The country has met some benchmarks (judicial reform, anti-corruption laws, vetting of judges and prosecutors), but Brussels remains skeptical about rule of law and organized crime. Rama's 2030 timeline is aspirational—most analysts predict 2033-2035 at the earliest. The government's approval rating hovers around 48-50%, buoyed by economic growth (4.1% in 2024, projected 3.8% in 2025), rising wages, and tourism booms (8.9 million visitors in 2024). But underneath, there's frustration: public services are poor, infrastructure crumbles outside Tirana, and corruption persists.

The May 2025 elections exposed Albania's democratic deficits. OSCE observers flagged the PS's systematic misuse of state resources—public employees pressured to campaign for the ruling party, government projects timed to coincide with the election, opposition parties denied access to public media. Rama's government has also faced corruption scandals that would topple administrations elsewhere. The incinerator scandal involved €110 million in contracts awarded to shell companies for waste incinerators that either don't exist or don't work—prosecutors are investigating, but no senior officials have been charged. Tirana mayor Erion Veliaj, a Rama ally, was arrested in 2024 on charges related to misuse of public funds; Kukës mayor Safet Gjici was detained for similar reasons. The 5D Affair involved a company tied to the government securing lucrative public contracts through opaque procurement processes. Yet Rama's PS won anyway—partly because the opposition is weak, partly because voters see corruption as endemic (the PD was equally corrupt when in power), and partly because the PS delivers: roads get built, the economy grows, and Albania feels more stable than it did a decade ago. Press freedom is declining: Albania ranks 96th on the Reporters Without Borders index, down from 83rd in 2019. Critical journalists face lawsuits, intimidation, and smear campaigns. The judiciary, while reformed, remains vulnerable to political pressure—the vetting process removed hundreds of corrupt judges, but appointments are still influenced by the ruling party. There's also concern about Rama's centralization of power: his dismissive attitude toward parliamentary oversight, his tendency to govern by decree, and his erosion of checks and balances suggest democratic backsliding.

The 2030 EU membership target will dominate Albanian politics through the next election (2029). Rama will push reforms to satisfy Brussels—more anti-corruption measures, organized crime crackdowns, judicial independence guarantees—but progress will be uneven. The EU is wary: Albania's track record on implementation is mixed, and there's fatigue in Brussels about Balkan enlargement. If Albania misses the 2030 deadline (likely), Rama will face a reckoning—his entire political project is built on EU accession, and failure could trigger a legitimacy crisis. The opposition will struggle to capitalize unless it reinvents itself: Berisha is a relic, and the PD needs younger leadership and a coherent platform beyond anti-Rama rhetoric. Watch for Rama's succession planning—he's been in power 12 years, and there's speculation he might step aside in 2027-2028 to become an EU commissioner or UN envoy, leaving his deputy, Belinda Balluku or Erion Veliaj (if cleared of charges), to take over. Albania's relationship with the U.S. remains strong—it's a NATO member, hosts American troops, and backed Washington on Ukraine and Israel. But relations with neighbors are tense: Serbia and Albania clash over Kosovo (which Tirana recognizes, Belgrade doesn't), and Greece disputes maritime borders and treatment of the Greek minority in southern Albania.

**Bottom line:** Rama has turned Albania into a one-party-dominant system, and unless the opposition gets its act together, he'll keep winning. His EU membership promise is a political masterstroke—it justifies every reform, excuses every shortfall, and keeps voters hopeful. But if Albania doesn't join by 2030-2032, the dream dies, and so might Rama's legacy. For now, he's untouchable—the economy works, the streets are safe, and Brussels is talking. The scandals? Albanians have seen worse.`,
    issues: ['Socialist Party dominance under Edi Rama', 'Corruption scandals despite electoral success', 'EU membership target of 2030', 'OSCE concerns about electoral fairness', 'Weak and divided opposition', 'Democratic backsliding and press freedom concerns']
