    lng: 3.0588,
    summary: `Abdelmadjid Tebboune won a second term as Algeria's president in September 2024 with 84.3% of the vote—or 94%, depending on which official figure you believe—but the real story was turnout: only 6 million of 24 million eligible voters bothered to show up. That's a 25% participation rate, the lowest since Algeria's independence in 1962, and it tells you everything about the country's political paralysis. Tebboune, a 78-year-old former housing minister and prime minister under Abdelaziz Bouteflika, was installed by the military in 2019 after mass protests (the Hirak movement) forced Bouteflika's resignation. The 2024 election was meant to legitimize Tebboune's rule, but instead it exposed the regime's hollow core: two token challengers (Islamist Abdelali Hassani Cherif with 3%, socialist Youcef Aouchiche with 2.1%), a disengaged electorate, and army Chief of Staff Said Chengriha pulling strings from the shadows. In November 2025, the government's attention-grabbing move was arresting French-Algerian writer Boualem Sansal for questioning Algeria's sovereignty over its eastern territories—a heavy-handed signal that dissent, even abroad, won't be tolerated. Meanwhile, legislative elections are scheduled for 2025, but both of Tebboune's presidential challengers were positioning for parliament, not the presidency—because Algerian law funds parties based on legislative seats, and they know the real power lies elsewhere. Algeria is a petrostate masquerading as a democracy, and in November 2025, the mask is slipping.

Algeria's political system is nominally a semi-presidential republic with a bicameral parliament, but in reality, it's a military-backed regime where elected institutions rubber-stamp decisions made by "le pouvoir" (the power)—an opaque network of military generals, intelligence chiefs, and business elites. President Tebboune is the civilian face, but Chief of Staff Said Chengriha wields considerable influence, especially on security, foreign policy, and oil revenues. Tebboune's first term (2019-2024) was defined by his attempts to distance himself from Bouteflika's corrupt legacy while maintaining the system that enabled it. He launched anti-corruption purges, arresting Bouteflika-era oligarchs like Issad Rebrab and Ali Haddad, but these were selective—designed to placate public anger, not dismantle networks. The cabinet is filled with technocrats loyal to Tebboune or the military, with key ministries (defense, interior, energy) controlled by military-aligned figures. The parliament is weak—dominated by parties that support Tebboune (the National Liberation Front, Democratic National Rally) and a smattering of opposition figures who lack influence. Algeria's economy is almost entirely dependent on hydrocarbons (oil and gas account for 95% of export revenues, 60% of state budget), which makes the government hostage to global energy prices. Tebboune has pushed economic diversification and import substitution to reduce reliance on foreign goods, but progress is minimal. Public sector employment is the main job creation mechanism—60% of workers are state employees. The regime's legitimacy rests on two pillars: distributing oil rents (subsidies, public sector jobs, cheap housing) and invoking the legacy of the independence struggle against France. But with oil revenues stagnating, youth unemployment at 30%, and inflation eroding purchasing power, that social contract is fraying.

The Hirak movement—mass protests that toppled Bouteflika in 2019—has been crushed. After Tebboune took office, security forces arrested prominent activists (Karim Tabbou, Khaled Drareni, Ibrahim Daoudji), banned protests under COVID-19 emergency laws, and maintained the crackdown even after the pandemic ended. In November 2025, political prisoners number in the hundreds, and Freedom House rates Algeria as "Not Free" (score: 34/100). The 2024 presidential election was a charade: the two challengers were carefully selected—Hassani Cherif and Aouchiche pose no threat to the regime—and the real opposition (including figures associated with the Hirak) was excluded. The 25% turnout shows Algerians' contempt: they didn't bother voting because they know it doesn't matter. The arrest of Boualem Sansal in November 2025 was a deliberate escalation: Sansal, a French-Algerian novelist, made controversial statements questioning Algeria's eastern borders (implying Morocco had legitimate claims). Algiers charged him with "threatening national unity," a signal to diaspora dissidents that criticizing the regime, even from abroad, carries consequences. Relations with France are toxic: Tebboune recalled Algeria's ambassador in 2021 after President Macron questioned whether Algeria existed as a nation before French colonization. Paris backed Morocco's autonomy plan for Western Sahara in 2024, further inflaming tensions. Algeria's support for the Polisario Front (which seeks independence for Western Sahara) puts it at odds with Morocco, and the two countries are locked in a regional cold war—closed borders, military buildups, and proxy battles for influence in the Sahel. Corruption remains endemic despite Tebboune's purges: Transparency International ranks Algeria 115th out of 180 countries. The military and intelligence services control vast economic sectors (construction, import licenses, real estate), and accountability is nonexistent.

The 2025 legislative elections will be carefully managed—expect pro-Tebboune parties to retain a majority, with just enough opposition seats (Islamists, socialists) to create the illusion of pluralism. The real question is what happens after Tebboune: he's 78, in declining health (he was hospitalized in Germany in 2020, rumored to have had a stroke), and there's no clear successor. The military will play kingmaker, likely selecting another pliable technocrat rather than risking genuine democratization. Algeria's youth are leaving in droves—thousands attempt the dangerous Mediterranean crossing to Europe each year (the "harraga" phenomenon). Those who stay are cynical, apolitical, and focused on survival, not activism. The regime's repression has worked in the short term—no Hirak 2.0 is visible—but underlying frustration is building. If oil prices crash or subsidies are cut, unrest could reignite. Algeria's foreign policy is shifting: it's deepening ties with Russia (arms deals, nuclear energy cooperation) and China (infrastructure projects, 5G), while distancing from the West. The U.S. maintains counterterrorism cooperation, but Washington has limited leverage. Algeria's role in the Sahel is growing—it mediates conflicts in Mali and Niger, positions itself as a stabilizing force, but also arms groups sympathetic to its interests. The 2026 African Cup of Nations, hosted by Algeria, will be a prestige project for the regime—an opportunity to showcase "stability" and "development," even as political freedoms contract.

**Bottom line:** Algeria is politically stagnant—an aging president, an entrenched military, and a population that's checked out. Tebboune's 94% "mandate" is a fiction; the 25% turnout is the reality. The regime survives because it controls oil revenues, security forces, and the narrative, but it has no vision beyond maintaining the status quo. The Hirak's spirit is suppressed but not dead. And when Tebboune exits—whether through poor health or a fixed term limit—Algeria faces a succession crisis with no democratic mechanism to resolve it. The petrostate model works until it doesn't.`,
    issues: ['Military-backed regime with weak democratic institutions', 'Tebboune reelection with only 25% voter turnout', 'Suppression of Hirak protest movement', 'Arrest of dissidents like Boualem Sansal', 'Dependence on oil revenues', 'Regional tensions with France and Morocco']
