    lng: 13.2344,
    summary: `November 2025 marked Angola's 50th anniversary of independence from Portugal, and President João Lourenço used the occasion to make a remarkable reconciliation gesture: he posthumously honored former opposition leaders Holden Roberto (FNLA) and Jonas Savimbi (UNITA) with the 50 Years of National Independence Medal, following appeals from civil society and the Catholic Church. For a country that fought a brutal 27-year civil war (1975-2002) and where the ruling MPLA (Popular Movement for the Liberation of Angola) has vilified Savimbi as a terrorist for decades, this was extraordinary—a signal that Lourenço, who also chairs the African Union as of February 2025, is serious about national reconciliation. But the symbolism masks harder political realities: the MPLA has ruled Angola since 1975, Lourenço is in his second and final term (constitutionally barred from a third), the party lost its absolute majority in the 2022 legislative elections (narrowly, 124 out of 220 seats) for the first time ever, and there's no clear successor. UNITA, the main opposition, now holds 90 seats and controls Luanda province—a stunning rebuke to the MPLA's dominance. Angola's politics in November 2025 are at an inflection point: Lourenço is trying to cement his reformist legacy (anti-corruption purges, economic diversification, political opening), but the MPLA's old guard resists change, UNITA smells blood, and 2027 elections loom with no obvious MPLA candidate. Local elections are on the agenda for 2025—Angola's first ever—and the MPLA is pushing parliament to finalize legislation before they lose more ground.

João Lourenço became president in 2017, succeeding José Eduardo dos Santos, who ruled Angola for 38 years (1979-2017). Lourenço was hand-picked by dos Santos as a loyal successor, but he immediately turned on his patron—sacking dos Santos's daughter Isabel (Africa's richest woman) from the state oil company Sonangol, arresting dos Santos's son José Filomeno for embezzlement, and dismantling the patronage networks that kept the dos Santos family in power. It was a political earthquake: Lourenço positioned himself as an anti-corruption reformer, recovering billions in stolen assets, but also purging rivals and consolidating his own faction within the MPLA. The 2022 legislative elections were a wake-up call: UNITA, led by Adalberto Costa Júnior, surged to 43.9% of the vote and won Luanda province, the MPLA's traditional stronghold. The MPLA retained 51.7% nationally and kept a parliamentary majority, but the loss of Luanda was humiliating—it showed that urban, young, and educated Angolans are tired of the MPLA's corruption and cronyism. Lourenço's government has pushed reforms: diversifying the economy away from oil (which still accounts for 90% of exports but whose revenues are volatile), privatizing state enterprises, attracting foreign investment, and improving the business climate. Angola's GDP grew 3.1% in 2024, driven by agriculture, construction, and services, but inflation remains high (13.2%), the kwanza is weak, and public debt is 80% of GDP. Lourenço's approval ratings are mixed—he's respected for tackling corruption and improving Angola's international standing (he mediated conflicts in the DRC and Great Lakes region, earning him the AU chair), but everyday Angolans struggle with joblessness, expensive food, and poor public services.

The MPLA's internal politics are opaque but fractious. Lourenço purged dos Santos loyalists, but the party's old guard (liberation war veterans, military brass, provincial bosses) view him as an outsider and reformer threatening their interests. The MPLA's dominance is built on patronage—control of oil revenues, state contracts, and public sector jobs—and Lourenço's anti-corruption push undermines that system. There's no clear successor: Lourenço is constitutionally barred from a third term, and potential candidates include Defense Minister João Ernesto dos Santos (no relation to the ex-president), Finance Minister Vera Daves, and Interior Minister Eugénio Laborinho. But none has Lourenço's stature or popular support, and factional infighting could weaken the MPLA heading into 2027. UNITA, meanwhile, is ascendant. Costa Júnior, a charismatic 61-year-old engineer, has energized the opposition—his rallies draw tens of thousands, his rhetoric emphasizes accountability and change, and he's built a coalition of urban youth, civil society, and disaffected MPLA voters. UNITA controls Luanda, Benguela, and Huambo provinces—Angola's economic and demographic heartlands—and if the 2027 elections are free and fair, they could win. But the MPLA controls the electoral commission, state media, and security forces, and the 2022 elections featured allegations of vote-rigging and intimidation. Local elections in 2025 will be a test: the MPLA is rushing to pass legislation because they fear losing municipalities to UNITA. The Catholic Church, civil society, and international observers are demanding transparency, but the MPLA's instinct is to tighten control, not loosen it.

The 2027 legislative elections will determine whether Angola transitions to genuine multiparty democracy or whether the MPLA entrenches one-party dominance through manipulation. If Lourenço's reforms succeed—reducing corruption, improving living standards, delivering local elections—the MPLA has a shot at retaining power. But if inflation stays high, jobs remain scarce, and the party's succession battle turns ugly, UNITA could win. Costa Júnior is the opposition's best chance in 50 years, but he faces an uphill battle: the MPLA controls state resources, the military, and the legal system. Expect the MPLA to delay local elections or gerrymander boundaries to limit UNITA gains. Lourenço's legacy depends on a smooth transition—if he installs a credible successor and delivers credible elections, he'll be remembered as the reformer who democratized Angola. If the MPLA collapses into infighting or rigging, his reforms will look like window dressing. Angola's regional role is expanding: Lourenço chairs the AU, mediated the DRC-Rwanda conflict, and is positioning Angola as a stability guarantor in southern Africa. Relations with the U.S. and EU are strong—Washington sees Lourenço as a counterweight to Chinese influence (Beijing is Angola's largest creditor), and Brussels is investing in renewable energy projects. But China remains Angola's top trade partner, holding $25 billion in debt—Luanda needs Beijing's goodwill, even as it diversifies relationships. The oil sector is slowly declining—production is falling, and Angola needs massive investment to maintain output. Lourenço's push for economic diversification (agriculture, tourism, manufacturing) is long-term, and short-term pain (high prices, weak kwanza) tests public patience.

**Bottom line:** Angola is at a crossroads. The MPLA's 50-year grip is loosening—they lost their absolute majority, they lost Luanda, and they lack a succession plan. Lourenço's reforms have opened political space, but the party's old guard and UNITA's momentum make 2027 unpredictable. The November 2025 gesture honoring Savimbi and Roberto is symbolic, but the real test is whether Angola can hold free elections and accept a potential UNITA victory. For now, the MPLA still has the power, but the writing's on the wall.`,
    issues: ['MPLA losing absolute majority for first time in 2022', 'João Lourenço succession uncertainty for 2027 elections', 'UNITA opposition surge in urban areas', 'First local elections scheduled for 2025', 'Anti-corruption reforms vs party old guard', 'Economic diversification from oil dependence']
